      <para id="id1170748775642">As a result of the high charge density, the Li<sup>+</sup> ion is a highly polarizing ion. One of the main consequences of this is that lithium tends to form polar covalent bonds rather than ionic interactions. For example, alkyl lithium compounds (RLi) contain covalent Li-C bonds in a similar manner to the Mg-C bonds in Grignards (RMgX, where X = Cl, Br). </para>
    </section>
    <section id="id1170741747556">
      <title>Lattice energy</title>
      <para id="id1170743207897">Lithium compounds have high lattice energies as compared to the other Group 1 metals (<link target-id="id1170740767484"/>). As a consequence Li<sub>2</sub>O, Li<sub>3</sub>N, and LiF are all insoluble in water, whereas their sodium compounds are highly soluble. </para>
